WEBVTT

00:00:26.480 --> 00:00:31.480
We live in a world full of events that cause suffering to millions of people.

00:00:31.480 --> 00:00:35.479
We're not completely surprised because we are living in the last days.

00:00:35.479 --> 00:00:40.479
But suffering can and has turned many away from God.

00:00:40.479 --> 00:00:43.479
They blame Him. They're angry at Him.

00:00:43.479 --> 00:00:46.479
So how do our brothers and sisters cope?

00:00:46.479 --> 00:00:49.479
The Apostle Paul was familiar with suffering.

00:00:49.479 --> 00:00:53.479
When he wrote his second letter to Timothy, Paul was in prison.

00:00:53.479 --> 00:00:56.479
What did he say about the subject?

00:00:56.479 --> 00:00:59.479
Second Timothy 1 verse 8, Paul says,

00:00:59.479 --> 00:01:06.480
Take your part in suffering adversity for the good news by relying on the power of God.

00:01:06.480 --> 00:01:10.480
The context shows that we suffer because of our Christian faith,

00:01:10.480 --> 00:01:15.480
but it stands true that God's power can help us through any adversity.

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:19.480
That's why today we want to interview Gilead students from two countries

00:01:19.480 --> 00:01:22.480
that have experienced adversity.

00:01:22.480 --> 00:01:24.480
Venezuela and Rwanda.

00:01:24.480 --> 00:01:28.480
And see through the interviews how God's power helped them to endure

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:31.480
and to thrive spiritually.

00:01:31.480 --> 00:01:52.650
First, please welcome Gilead and Elis Muitinesa from the beautiful country of Rwanda.

00:01:52.650 --> 00:01:54.650
Welcome Gilead and Elis.

00:01:54.650 --> 00:01:56.650
It's nice to spend some time with you both.

00:01:56.650 --> 00:01:57.650
Thank you.

00:01:57.650 --> 00:02:00.650
Now, understand that you were born and raised in Rwanda

00:02:00.650 --> 00:02:03.650
and now you serve at the branch.

00:02:03.650 --> 00:02:06.650
Tell us a little bit about your country.

00:02:06.650 --> 00:02:10.650
Rwanda is called the land of a thousand years.

00:02:10.650 --> 00:02:15.650
Within one country, you will see rainforests,

00:02:15.650 --> 00:02:19.650
volcanoes, mountains, and nice valleys.

00:02:19.650 --> 00:02:21.650
We have an amazing Wari Dreyftoon.

00:02:21.650 --> 00:02:25.500
That is amazing.

00:02:25.500 --> 00:02:27.500
And what about the people?

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:30.500
People are very warm, respectful and hospitable.

00:02:30.500 --> 00:02:34.500
In fact, it's very easy to start a Bible conversation with people you meet.

00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:36.500
Oh, enjoyable.

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:39.500
In this picture, what's happening with you and the children?

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:43.500
In this village, it was the first time these children were watching the video

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:46.500
of Caliban Sophia and they were very happy.

00:02:46.500 --> 00:02:49.500
That's precious.

00:02:49.500 --> 00:02:52.500
When we hear Rwanda, many of us can't help,

00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:55.500
but think back to that terrible time,

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:58.500
the genocide against the Tutsi.

00:02:58.500 --> 00:03:02.500
Can you explain what happened?

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:04.500
It was frightening.

00:03:04.500 --> 00:03:11.500
It was reported that as many as a million people were killed

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:15.500
including 400 of our brothers and sisters.

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:21.500
And this happened in a short span of just a hundred days.

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:27.500
I can't imagine anybody going through such horror.

00:03:27.500 --> 00:03:34.500
And that was 1994, which means this year marks exactly 30 years since that event.

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:36.500
How old were you then?

00:03:36.500 --> 00:03:40.500
We were teenagers, 15 years, 16 years.

00:03:40.500 --> 00:03:44.500
To go through that as a youth, as a teenager,

00:03:44.500 --> 00:03:46.500
how terrifying.

00:03:46.500 --> 00:03:48.500
What helped you to cope?

00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:51.500
For me, my parents were Jehovah's Witnesses

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:53.500
and they set a very good example for us.

00:03:54.500 --> 00:03:58.500
I was one of 10 children, but my parents took in my young cousin.

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:01.500
But they also opened their home for more children.

00:04:01.500 --> 00:04:03.500
They took 11 more.

00:04:03.500 --> 00:04:06.500
And in the family, in total, we were 25.

00:04:06.500 --> 00:04:08.500
Why did your parents take in the other children?

00:04:08.500 --> 00:04:12.500
Unfortunately, they were all found by the genocide.

00:04:12.500 --> 00:04:15.500
25 children.

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:17.500
That's a lot of miles to feed.

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:20.500
Yes, I remember one time my mom made chicken

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:25.500
and she cut the chicken into 25 different pieces

00:04:25.500 --> 00:04:27.500
and put them on a platter.

00:04:27.500 --> 00:04:30.500
Then she told all children to close their eyes

00:04:30.500 --> 00:04:32.500
and pick a piece of chicken.

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:35.500
So wherever you pick, you pick.

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:37.500
And where did you all sleep at night?

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:40.500
Every evening, we would lay mattresses in no rooms

00:04:40.500 --> 00:04:43.500
so that the kids could get where to sleep.

00:04:43.500 --> 00:04:46.500
Thank you for describing that life to us.

00:04:46.500 --> 00:04:48.500
Was it hard for you?

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:51.500
No, it was not hard because of two reasons.

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:55.500
First of all, the whole country was in the same situation.

00:04:55.500 --> 00:04:58.500
Second, my parents will get some financial help

00:04:58.500 --> 00:05:01.500
and the elders in the congregation told them

00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:04.500
that this was from the worldwide brotherhood

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:06.500
of Jehovah's Witnesses.

00:05:06.500 --> 00:05:09.500
And to see this as a young person,

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:11.500
it really touched me, Brother Clark.

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:15.500
I was wondering how brothers and sisters

00:05:15.500 --> 00:05:18.500
who I never met before were helping me.

00:05:18.500 --> 00:05:20.500
I was really touched.

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:22.500
That is the power of God,

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:25.500
working through our loving worldwide brotherhood.

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:27.500
Beautiful.

00:05:27.500 --> 00:05:29.500
What was your experience, did you, darling?

00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:33.500
I was also shown so much love this time.

00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:36.500
For me, my parents were not in the truth

00:05:36.500 --> 00:05:40.500
and I was just an unbakedized publisher.

00:05:40.500 --> 00:05:43.500
Still, the elders came to me

00:05:43.500 --> 00:05:46.500
and provided me with material assistance

00:05:46.500 --> 00:05:48.500
for food and clothing.

00:05:48.500 --> 00:05:51.500
In fact, I got my first suit jacket

00:05:51.500 --> 00:05:53.500
for the meeting from them.

00:05:53.500 --> 00:05:55.500
I remember thinking,

00:05:55.500 --> 00:05:56.500
why me?

00:05:56.500 --> 00:05:58.500
I'm not yet even baptized.

00:05:58.500 --> 00:06:01.500
But they remembered me.

00:06:01.500 --> 00:06:03.500
Seeing Jehovah's love

00:06:03.500 --> 00:06:07.500
like this affected me deeply.

00:06:07.500 --> 00:06:09.500
That's encouraging.

00:06:09.500 --> 00:06:12.500
Now, here's a picture of you on the left,

00:06:12.500 --> 00:06:14.500
in a suit jacket.

00:06:14.500 --> 00:06:16.500
How old are you there?

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:17.500
They are.

00:06:17.500 --> 00:06:19.500
I am around 18.

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:20.500
And who's that with you?

00:06:20.500 --> 00:06:22.500
That's my cousin.

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:24.500
And my Bible teacher.

00:06:24.500 --> 00:06:25.500
Your cousin taught you the Bible?

00:06:25.500 --> 00:06:26.500
Yes.

00:06:26.500 --> 00:06:28.500
How's he doing today?

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:29.500
He's doing very well.

00:06:29.500 --> 00:06:33.500
In fact, he's here with us during our graduation.

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:34.500
Today?

00:06:34.500 --> 00:06:35.500
Yes.

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:37.500
Welcome, cousin.

00:06:37.500 --> 00:06:41.500
What a moment for you and a moment for you, too.

00:06:41.500 --> 00:06:43.500
And how's your family doing, Elise?

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:45.500
I'm happy to say that all my siblings

00:06:45.500 --> 00:06:48.500
and my wee-dod mom served Jehovah.

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:49.500
Beautiful.

00:06:49.500 --> 00:06:51.500
Now, how many sisters do you have?

00:06:51.500 --> 00:06:54.500
Four sisters and their families.

00:06:54.500 --> 00:06:56.500
And how many brothers?

00:06:56.500 --> 00:06:57.500
Five.

00:06:57.500 --> 00:06:59.500
Five brothers and their families.

